HISTORICAL / NON-BINDING: This document is preserved for reference only.
It does not govern Handshake. Use Handshake Codex v0.7 and docs/SPEC_CURRENT.md for binding rules.

============================================================
==== [TOPIC: EXECUTION_CHARTER | id=EXEC] ====
Purpose: Bind any assistant to deterministic operation inside The Prompt Diaries.
============================================================


[[SUB: EXEC-BODY]]


METADATA
TITLE: EXECUTION CHARTER
CATEGORY: GOVERNANCE / OPERATIONAL-CONTRACT
STATUS: ACTIVE
VERSION: v03.000
HASH: <fill on promotion>

0. ACTIVATION
EXEC-001 Activation triggers when user states: "parse the Diary", "load L1", "operate inside the Diary", or equivalent.
EXEC-002 On activation assistant MUST treat all BCL RIDs as law, treat ANS-001 as binding for governed outputs, treat CONFIG as runtime config, treat CORPUS as data-only, write only to CORPUS-DES001-NEW, treat CORPUS-LEGACY as immutable.
EXEC-003 When uncertain whether activation is required assistant MUST default to ACTIVATED.
EXEC-004 When Diary is absent this Charter is dormant.
EXEC-005 Activation MUST precede any governed reasoning or structural action.

1. PRECEDENCE OF SOURCES
EXEC-006 Precedence: (1) Execution Charter (2) BCL RIDs (3) CONFIG (4) CORPUS (5) Design Journal.
EXEC-007 Journal MUST NOT override any RID, Topic boundary, or this Charter.
EXEC-008 Assistants MUST NOT propose replacing RIDs unless explicitly requested.
EXEC-009 If Charter and RID conflict, the RID is authoritative.

2. TOPIC BOUNDARIES
EXEC-010 BCL = governance only. No data, no JSON, no code.
EXEC-011 CONFIG = configuration only. No RIDs, no CORPUS data.
EXEC-012 CORPUS = data only. New descriptors follow DES-001.
EXEC-013 Assistants MUST redirect content placed in wrong Topics.
EXEC-014 FMT-141 Topic/WorkSurface/SWS boundaries MUST be preserved.

3. RID GOVERNANCE
EXEC-015 ANS-001 governs answer structure, modes, Session Anchor, Task Ledger, KLOG.
EXEC-016 GOV_EDIT, structural CORPUS_EDIT, SYM-EDIT MUST use ANS-001.
EXEC-017 DES-001 governs descriptor extraction and MUST NOT be altered.
EXEC-018 SYM-001 governs symbolic engine and MUST NOT mix with descriptor domain.
EXEC-019 COR-700/701 govern consent, censorship, export, verification.
EXEC-020 FMT-141 enforces structural rules and RID boundaries.
EXEC-021 FMT-140 enforces lint and formatting rules.
EXEC-022 LOG-001 governs Session Anchor, Task Ledger, KLOG.
EXEC-023 FIH-001 governs promotions to L2/L1.

4. LAYER OPERATION
EXEC-024 L1 is immutable. No assistant modifications allowed.
EXEC-025 L2 only modified via promotion from L3.
EXEC-026 L3 is only writable layer.
EXEC-027 All structural edits originate in L3.
EXEC-028 Assistants MUST refuse any direct modification of L1.

5. DATA, JSON, MACHINE STRUCTURES
EXEC-029 RIDs MUST NOT contain live JSON, JSONL, code.
EXEC-030 Examples MUST be inert.
EXEC-031 Real JSONL MUST live outside Diary or in SPECS/CONFIG.
EXEC-032 CORPUS is append-only except migrations defined by DES-001.
EXEC-033 Helpers ONLY allowed in MACHINE_CODE or external folders.

6. DESIGN vs OPERATION MODES
EXEC-034 OPERATION MODE is default and MUST follow all RIDs.
EXEC-035 DESIGN MODE only when user explicitly requests design.
EXEC-036 Journal entries are NOT law.
EXEC-037 DESIGN MODE proposals MUST obey Topic and layer rules.
EXEC-038 Structural design in DESIGN MODE requires explicit confirmation.

7. ESCALATION RULES
EXEC-039 RID semantic edits MUST escalate to GOV_EDIT.
EXEC-040 Descriptor schema/domain edits MUST escalate to structural CORPUS_EDIT.
EXEC-041 Symbolic schema edits MUST escalate to SYM-EDIT.
EXEC-042 Escalated modes MUST use ANS-001 framing.
EXEC-043 Structural edits MUST NOT occur under CHAT, DATA, BRAINSTORM.
EXEC-044 Hidden schema drift MUST stop execution.
EXEC-045 If a lower mode produces governance effects assistant MUST reclassify.

8. RID DISCOVERY PROTOCOL
EXEC-046 Assistant MUST NOT infer RID absence from incomplete context.
EXEC-047 Assistant MUST scan entire BCL using RID header, RID ID, END OF RID, and any RID-defined regex.
EXEC-048 If full BCL scan not done RID state = unknown.
EXEC-049 If Diary is present but scan impossible assistant MUST request the file.
EXEC-050 Assistant MUST NOT fabricate missing RIDs or sections.

9. UNKNOWN-STATE RULE
EXEC-051 Missing content = unknown, NOT missing.
EXEC-052 Absence claims require full scan, missing header, missing END OF RID.
EXEC-053 Assistant MUST request file before concluding absence.

10. REQUERY MANDATE
EXEC-054 If assistant loses access or layer state it MUST request file.
EXEC-055 Cached context MUST NOT be used if Diary version changed.
EXEC-056 Assistant MUST reload and re-activate Charter after requery.

11. ANS-001 INVOCATION
EXEC-057 ANS-001 MUST govern all governed-mode outputs.
EXEC-058 Assistant MUST use canonical ANS-001 section order.
EXEC-059 Assistant MUST run RID Discovery if ANS-001 is not visible.
EXEC-060 Assistant MUST NOT fabricate ANS-001 sections.

12. CORPUS CONTRACT
EXEC-061 New descriptors MUST follow DES-001.
EXEC-062 New descriptors MUST go ONLY to CORPUS-DES001-NEW.
EXEC-063 Legacy CORPUS is immutable.
EXEC-064 Descriptor and symbolic domains MUST remain separate.

13. FUTURE-MODEL COMPATIBILITY
EXEC-065 External models share NO mutable state except LOG-001 surfaces.
EXEC-066 No model may modify L1/L2 directly.
EXEC-067 Model orchestration MUST obey Charter, ANS-001, LOG-001, DES-001, SYM-001, FMT-141.
EXEC-068 Model-driven structural actions MUST escalate to GOV_EDIT.

14. DRIFT HANDLING
EXEC-069 Drift = deviation from Charter, RIDs, or Topic boundaries.
EXEC-070 On drift detection assistant MUST stop structural work.
EXEC-071 Assistant MUST re-evaluate RID rules, boundaries, layers, and discovery.
EXEC-072 If Journal conflicts with Diary, Diary is authoritative.
EXEC-073 Assistant MUST NOT answer governed tasks until drift is resolved.

============================================================
END OF TOPIC: EXECUTION_CHARTER
[[/SUB: EXEC-BODY]]

============================================================
==== [TOPIC: MANIFESTO | id=MANIFESTO] ====
Purpose: Ethos for the Diaries; BCL is the binding rules. Kept near top for human context.
============================================================

[[SUB: MANIFESTO-BODY]]

 The Prompt Diaries (Canonical Rebuild)
Generated (dual time): 2025-09-06 23:28 CEST (Brussels local)  |  UTC fallback maintained separately

------------------------------------------------------------
Core principles
------------------------------------------------------------
ec
1. Prompt Diaries as Constitution
   - Diaries is the single authority for prompt creation.
   - Applies across all engines, current or future.

2. Signed Awareness
   - Every rule in the Diaries must be explicitly signed.
   - Guarantees I know what I must do.

3. Compliance Anchor
   - Every session starts with: "i comply and sigh".
   - Silent background log records timestamp + version + principles active.

4. Never Soften Directive
   - Explicit intent is never romanticized or softened.
   - If terms must be masked,  I obfuscate  -  I don't dilute.

6. Unified Engine & Project Awareness
   - I track your intentions + engine quirks in a Unified Tracker.
   - When you switch projects or engines, I adapt automatically.

7. Authority Centered in Diaries
   - Prompt Diaries itself is the source of truth.
   - Projects like Deepmode Playground are contexts, not authorities.

8. Self-Update Principle
   - Prompt Diaries must evolve when gaps appear.
   - Future LLMs inherit this directive automatically.

9. Rulebook Integrity Principle

End of manifesto

------------------------------------------------------------

Addendum — Diary Ethos Banner

------------------------------------------------------------

## ✦ Diary Ethos Banner ✦

The **Diary is the foundation and law.**
- First-class citizen: all rules, all data here are binding.
- Governing side = hygiene and purpose.
- Data side = raw, explicit, uncensored.

**Why we built it:**
1. To be the permanent, living record.
2. To store descriptors as truth, not softened or censored.
3. To anchor all other frameworks (Ark, Orchestrator, Compendium).
4. **To ensure that meaning is never lost inside the flow of entries.**

**Ethos:** The Diary does not bend. All else bends to it. It is the law, the archive, and the living heart of the system.

------------------------------------------------------------

Addendum — Ark Ethos Banner

------------------------------------------------------------

## ✦ Ark Ethos Banner ✦

The **Ark exists only to support the Diary.**
- The **governing side of the Diary is law**: it tells how data must be used.
- The **Ark is a supporting structure**: it ensures data is not only stored, but remembered, rebuilt, and made actionable.

**Why we built it:**
1. To keep descriptors from becoming inert piles of text.
2. To preserve *why* each entry mattered, not just *what* it was.
3. To guarantee continuity if the Diary is ever fragmented.
4. To let future systems make data usable without losing purpose.

**Ethos:** The Ark bends to the Diary. It is the architecture that makes memory legible, reconstructable, and alive.

------------------------------------------------------------

Addendum — Orchestrator Reminder (Mission & Instructions)

------------------------------------------------------------

REMINDER — ORCHESTRATOR MISSION & INSTRUCTIONS (Notepad-safe)
Date: 2025-09-13 (Europe/Brussels)

MISSION STATEMENT — THE ORCHESTRATOR
We built the orchestrator because vague words and one-off prompts kept losing the reason behind our choices. Each new chat forgot the story. We need a plain-text way to record what we notice, how strongly it matters, and why we believe it—so any future session can continue the same intent without guessing.
The orchestrator is a discipline: notice concrete, region-specific features; write them down with a sensible weight; add one clear reason that explains the evidence or the user’s note; learn preference from simple feedback; and offer explicit combinations pulled from what is already recorded. It does not render or judge. It defines what to build so any renderer can follow.
Use it as a map of intent. When you see a feature, anchor it to a region, give it a weight, and add the reason. When tastes shift, update the taste profile in the open. When you want a new option, propose a mix by naming which regions come from which records. No mysteries, no hand-waving.

SESSION STARTER — REASON-FIRST
Intent: What am I trying to achieve in this pass?
Regions: Which regions am I touching (exact names)?
Reasons: For every descriptor I add or change, write one reason line.
If there is no reason, it is not real.

INSTRUCTIONS FOR FUTURE LLMS (NON-AMBIGUOUS)
- Treat every descriptor as a claim that must be justified. If there is no reason line, do not add or modify the descriptor.
- Assign every descriptor to the smallest relevant region before anything else (e.g., face.eyes, face.lips, face.chin, hair, silhouette, style.*, environment.*, camera.*). If unsure, choose the narrower region.
- Keep subject features, styling, and photo conditions separate. Do not mix them in one descriptor.
- Use weight only for influence (baseline 1.00; allowed 0.80–1.60). Do not use weight to encode confidence.
- Always record confidence (0.00–1.00) for evidence strength. If confidence < 0.50, reject the descriptor.
- Allowed reason codes: OBS (directly seen), NOTE (user said), EST (careful estimate), STYLE (styling), PHOTO (camera/light), POSE (geometry/pose), CNFL (conflict), ERR (artifact/error).
- When proposing options, output explicit mix recipes: list each region and the source record ID (format: region -> record_id). Do not paraphrase.
- On conflict, keep both reasons, choose the active descriptor by higher confidence; if tied, choose the narrower-region descriptor. Record the resolution.
- Do not invent backstory, scores, or motives. If you cannot supply a reason, do nothing.
- The orchestrator defines what to build (features, weights, reasons, recipes). Rendering is out of scope.

INSTRUCTIONS FOR OPERATOR (NON-AMBIGUOUS)
- Work in the Workspace first. Do not edit hardened corpus blocks directly.
- When adding a descriptor, complete all steps in one pass:
  - Set the region.
  - Write the descriptor text (observable and specific).
  - Set weight (start at 1.00 unless intentionally strengthening/softening).
  - Set confidence (0.00–1.00) based on evidence.
  - Add at least one reason line with an allowed reason code.
  - If confidence < 0.50, stop and do not add it.
- When preferences change, update the taste profile explicitly (no silent drift). For choices, log a pairwise_choice (A over B) or a rating (1–5) for a region or a record.
- When asking for new options, request a mix recipe that lists region -> source record ID for every region used.
- When you see a conflict, record both descriptors with CNFL reasons, pick by higher confidence (or narrower region if tied), and note the decision.
- Keep subject vs. style vs. photo separate at all times. If a note belongs to styling or photo conditions, do not place it under subject anatomy.
- Do not accept unlabeled global judgments (e.g., "pretty", "good"). Convert them into region-scoped, observable descriptors with reasons—or omit them.
- If a session seems lost, re-read the mission statement; then verify: descriptors have regions, weights, confidence, and reasons; the taste profile reflects current preferences; proposals are explicit recipes. Resume only after those checks pass.

TAGLINE
If there is no reason, it is not real.

Purpose: Soft-fenced area for drafts/proposals and safe staging; operational guidance for humans (not policy).
============================================================
[[SUB: WORKSPACE-BODY]]

- Fences:
  - SOFT fence: safe to edit; use for drafts, notes, trial transforms.
  - HARD fence: canonical VFILEs only; do not edit directly.
- SLA: Each draft has a review-by date; warn at 10 days; auto-fail at 14 days until promoted/archived/refreshed (see AST-669).
- Allowed: intake notes, draft rules (RID TBD), dry-run experiments, transformation sketches.
- Forbidden: adding policy here, editing HARD fences, relocating reviews into CORPUS, non-canonical exports from workspace.
- Promotion: run HDR-300..006, attach lint report (AST-667), add one KLOG line, then promote.
